Robert Charronâ€™s Murder-Suicide At Les Racines de vie Montessori Daycare
Published April 3, 2020 by Christopher di Armani
Filed Under: Canadian Mass Murders, Guns, Human Depravity, Suicide
This is part of my ongoing series on Canadian Mass Murders.
[ Technically, not a mass murder, but Iâ€™m including it in this series because the killerâ€™s attempt to kill his estranged wife failed and a firearm was used. ]
On Friday, April 5, 2013, Robert Charron walked into the Les Racines de vie Montessori day care in Gatineau, Quebec, executed a 38-year-old man in front of the children, then killed himself, but not before dousing his estranged wife, the day careâ€™s Director,Â  in â€œa flammable liquidâ€ and attempting to set her on fire.
She was able to escape.
In Canada for about a year after obtaining permanent resident status, Neil Galliou was not so lucky. He was shot once in the face and once in the stomach.
Quebec Coroner Marie Pinaultâ€™s report said the murder-suicide was the result of Robert Charronâ€™s devastation over his separation from his wife.
Gatineau Police Chief Mario Harel saidÂ Neil Galliou had no personal involvement with Charronâ€™s wife, despite wide speculation. It is unknown why the murderer targeted Galliou.
â€œWe donâ€™t have any â€” any â€” information that thereâ€™s somebody else in the picture,â€ Chief Harel said.
Robert Charron was identified as an â€œavid hunterâ€.

